{"title_page": "Family of Dwight D. Eisenhower", "text_new": "{{short description|List of members of the family of Dwight D. Eisenhower}}\n{{Infobox family\n| name          = The Eisenhower family\n| image         = Birthday Party for Anne Eisenhower-cropped.jpg\n| image_size    = 250\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Birthday Party for granddaughter Anne Eisenhower (not shown). From left to right around the table: [[John Eisenhower]], [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], [[Mamie Eisenhower]], [[Barbara Eisenhower]], and [[David Eisenhower]] with his back to the camera.\n| region        = United States ([[Texas]], [[Kansas]], [[Washington, D.C.]])\n| early_forms   =\n| members       = [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], [[Mamie Eisenhower]], [[David Eisenhower]], [[Anne Eisenhower]], [[Susan Eisenhower]], [[Mary Jean Eisenhower]]\n| otherfamilies = \n| distinctions  =\n| traditions    = \n| heirlooms     =\n| estate        =\n| meaning       =\n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\nThe family of [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]<!-- No bolding! See MOS:BOLDTITLE -->, the 34th [[President of the United States]], and his wife. [[Mamie Eisenhower|Mamie]], is made up of people of [[German people|German]] and [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] descent. They are related by marriage to the family of [[Richard Nixon]], who was Eisenhower's vice-president, and was later the 37th president of the United States.\n\nthis is wrong \n christopher cox says he has no children but he hAS TWO\n\n== Family background ==\n[[File:Eisenhower House.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|The Eisenhower family home, [[Abilene, Kansas]]]]\nThe Eisenhauer (German for \"iron hewer/miner\") family migrated from [[Karlsbrunn]] in [[Nassau-Saarbr\u00fccken]], to America, first settling in [[York, Pennsylvania]], in 1741, and in the 1880s moving to Kansas.<ref name=\"barnett19421109\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JUAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA112| title=General \"Ike\" Eisenhower | work=Life | date=November 9, 1942 | accessdate=May 31, 2011 | author=Barnett, Lincoln | page=112}}</ref> Accounts vary as to how and when the German name Eisenhauer was [[anglicized]] to Eisenhower.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YVD0jK03EPEC | title=Ike: An American Hero | author=Korda, Michael | year=2007 | accessdate=July 22, 2012 | page=63}}</ref> Eisenhower's [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] ancestors, who were primarily farmers, included Hans Nikolaus Eisenhauer of Karlsbrunn, who migrated to [[Lancaster, Pennsylvania]], in 1741.<ref name=\"Ambrose 1983, p. 14\">{{harvnb|Ambrose|1983|p=14}}</ref>\n\n==Parents and siblings==\n{{main|Ida Stover Eisenhower}}\nThe great grandson of Hans Nikolaus Eisenhauer was Jacob Eisenhower, a Kansas farmer. Jacob's son, David Jacob Eisenhower (1863\u20131942), was Dwight D. Eisenhower's father. David Jacob was a college-educated engineer, despite his own father Jacob's urging to stay on the family farm. David owned a general store in [[Hope, Kansas]], but the business failed due to economic conditions and the family became impoverished. The Eisenhowers then lived in Texas from 1889 until 1892, and later returned to Kansas, with $24 ({{Inflation|US|24|1892|fmt=eq}}) to their name at the time. David worked as a railroad mechanic and then at a creamery.<ref name=\"Ambrose 1983, pp. 16\u20138\" />\n\nEisenhower's mother, [[Ida Stover Eisenhower|Ida Elizabeth (Stover) Eisenhower]], born in Virginia, of German Protestant ancestry, moved to Kansas from Virginia. She married David on September 23, 1885, in [[Lecompton, Kansas]], on the campus of their alma mater, [[Lane University]].<ref name=\"Ambrose 1983, pp. 16\u20138\">{{harvnb|Ambrose|1983|pp=16\u20138}}</ref>\n\nBy 1898, the parents made a decent living and provided a suitable home for their large family.<ref>{{harvnb|Ambrose|1983|p=19}}</ref> They had seven children, all sons, of whom one died in infancy.\n\n*Arthur Eisenhower (1886\u2013January 27, 1958)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/01/27/archives/arthur-eisenhower-dies-in-kansas-city-a-b-eisenhower-dies-in.html|title=Arthur Eisenhower Dies in Kansas City; A. B. EISENHOWER DIES IN MISSOURI|first=the Associated|last=Press|date=27 January 1958|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n*[[Edgar Newton Eisenhower]] (January 19, 1889 \u2013 July 12, 1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/07/13/archives/edgar-e-isenhower-late-presidents-b-tother-dies-lawyer-21-months.html|title=Edgar Eisenhower, Late President's Brother, Dies|date=13 July 1971|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n*Dwight David Eisenhower (October 14, 1890 \u2013 March 28, 1969)\n*Roy Eisenhower (1892\u2013June 7, 1942)<ref>Carlo D'Este, ''Eisenhower: A Soldier's Life'' (2003), p. 298.</ref>\n*[[Earl Dewey Eisenhower]] (February 1, 1898 \u2013 December 18, 1968)\n*[[Milton Stover Eisenhower]] (September 15, 1899 \u2013 May 2, 1985)\n*Paul Dawson Eisenhower (May 12, 1894 \u2013 March 16, 1895)\n\nOf these, Milton was the most notable of the brothers other than Dwight. Milton became an American educational administrator, serving as president of three major American universities: [[Kansas State University]] (1943\u20131950), [[Pennsylvania State University]] (1950\u20131956), and [[Johns Hopkins University]] (1956\u20131957). On October 12, 1927, Eisenhower married Helen Elsie Eakin (1904\u20131954), with whom he had a son, Milton Stover Eisenhower, Jr., in 1930 and a daughter, Ruth Eakin Eisenhower, in 1938.\n\nEarl also achieved a measure of notability, having been elected to a term in the Illinois House of Representatives, from 1965 to 1967. Earl married Kathryn McIntyre Snyder in 1933, with whom he had two children.\n\nEdgar graduated from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1914,<ref>''Who's Who in America, Volume XXX 1958-1959'' (1958). Chicago: A.N. Marquis Co.</ref> and began practicing law in 1915 in [[Tacoma, Washington]]; he became was known as a \"shoot from the hip ultraconservative.\"<ref>Obituary from the Kansas City ''Times'', July 13, 1971</ref> Edgar was married three times, first to Louise Alexander Eisenhower (1893\u20131946) in 1911, then to Bernice Thompson Eisenhower (1902\u20131948) in 1930, and finally to Lucille Dawson Eisenhower (1921\u20132012) in 1951. Edgar had two children, both with his first wife, Merrill Jack Eisenhower (1916\u20131956), and Janis Louise Eisenhower Causin (1922\u20132000).\n\n==Immediate family==\n<!--Please don't remove [[Template:Anchor|anchor template]] (or edit the name within their doubled, curly brackets). Thanks!-->\n\n===Mamie Eisenhower===\n[[File:Mamie eisenhower.gif|thumb|upright=0.9|Mamie Eisenhower, painted in 1953 by Thomas E. Stephens]]\n{{main|Mamie Eisenhower}}\nWhile Eisenhower was stationed in Texas, he met [[Mamie Eisenhower|Mamie Doud]] of [[Boone, Iowa]].{{r|barnett19421109}}\n\nDoud was the second child born to John Sheldon Doud (1870\u20131951), a [[Meat packing industry|meatpacking]] executive, and his wife, Elivera Mathilda Carlson (1878\u20131960).<ref name=\"Susan Eisenhower 2002\">Susan Eisenhower, \"Mrs. Ike: Memories and Reflections on the Life of Mamie Eisenhower\" (Capitol Books, 2002)</ref><ref name=nrhp>{{cite web |url=http://www.coloradohistory-oahp.org/programareas/register/1503/cty/pdfs/5DV747.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form |author=Tatanka Historical Associates |access-date=February 4, 2009 |work=www.coloradohistory-oahp.org |publisher=Colorado Historical Society Office of Archeology & Historic Preservation |date=February 25, 2005 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060816015657/http://www.coloradohistory-oahp.org/programareas/register/1503/cty/pdfs/5DV747.pdf |archive-date=August 16, 2006 }}</ref> She grew up in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]], [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], [[Denver, Colorado]], and the Doud winter home in [[San Antonio, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstladies.org/biographies/firstladies.aspx?biography=35 |title=Mamie Eisenhower Biography |publisher=National First Ladies Library |access-date=December 27, 2013 }}</ref> Her father, who retired at age 36, ran a meatpacking company founded by his father, Doud & Montgomery (\"Buyers of Live Hogs\"), and had investments in Illinois and Iowa stockyards.<ref name=\"Susan Eisenhower 2002\"/> Her mother was a daughter of Swedish immigrants.<ref name=\"Susan Eisenhower 2002\"/> She had three sisters: Eleanor Carlson Doud, Eda Mae Doud, and Mabel Frances \"Mike\" Doud.<ref name=\"Susan Eisenhower 2002\"/><ref name=nrhp />\n\nDoud and Eisenhower were immediately taken with each other. He proposed to her on Valentine's Day in 1916.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/publications/publicroads/03mar/05.cfm | title =The Man Who Changed America, Part I | author =Richard F. Weingroff | publisher =fhwa.dot.gov | date =March\u2013April 2003}}</ref> A November wedding date in Denver was moved up to July 1 due to the pending U.S. entry into World War&nbsp;I. They moved many times during their first 35 years of marriage.<ref>{{harvnb|Ambrose|1983|pp=59\u201360}}</ref>\n\n===Children===\nThe Eisenhowers had two sons, Doud Dwight \"Icky\" Eisenhower, and John Eisenhower.\n\n====Doud Eisenhower====\n[[File:Doudeisenhower.jpg|thumb|Doud with his parents, [[Mamie Eisenhower|Mamie]] and [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Dwight]].]]\n\nDoud Dwight Eisenhower (September 24, 1917&nbsp;\u2013 January 2, 1921) was the first son of Dwight and Mamie Eisenhower. He was named \"Doud\" in honor of his mother (whose maiden name was Doud) and \"Dwight\" in honor of his father. He was commonly called \"Ikky\" (pronounced as \"icky\") by his parents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/12/upshot/ike-and-his-sons-the-grief-of-a-supreme-commander-and-a-father.html |title=D-Day Wasn't the First Time Eisenhower Felt as if He Had Lost a Son |newspaper=The New York Times |first=Michael |last=Beschloss |department=The Upshot |date=June 11, 2014 |access-date=June 16, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=Berger-Knorr, Lawrence|title=The Pennsylvania Relations of Dwight D. Eisenhower|page=8}}</ref>\n\nDoud was born in [[San Antonio, Texas]], then he and his mother moved to [[Denver]], [[Colorado]] while his father was stationed at [[Fort George G. Meade|Camp Meade]] in [[Maryland]].<ref name=icky>{{cite web |url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/infrastructure/ichy.cfm |title=Icky |publisher=Federal Highway Administration |work=www.fhwa.dot.gov |accessdate=November 24, 2011 }}</ref> Regarding Dwight's family contacts while on the U.S. Army's 1919 [[Transcontinental Motor Convoy]], biographers Lester and Irene David wrote:\n<blockquote>He called Mamie several times a week [while on the convoy], beginning each call with requests for news about Icky. How was he growing? What new mischief had he gotten into? Once Mamie interrupted with, \"Listen here...how about asking how your wife is?\" Chastened; Ike chatted for a moment about Mamie but soon turned the conversation to Icky again. Mamie gave up.<ref name=icky/></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Eisenhowerdoudd.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Grave of Doud Dwight Eisenhower in [[Eisenhower Presidential Center|Eisenhower Center]]]]\nAfter he and his family relocated to [[Fort George G. Meade|Fort Meade]] in [[Severn, Maryland|Severn]], [[Maryland]], his mother hired a 16-year-old local girl as a maid. She had been recovering from [[scarlet fever]].<ref name=icky/> In December 1920, shortly before [[Christmas]], Ikky caught scarlet fever from her.<ref name=icky/> Though his mother tried desperately to save him, even calling a specialist from [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]] in [[Baltimore]],<ref name=icky/> Ikky died on January 2, 1921. His [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|father]] referred to this incident as \"the most shattering moment of their lives, one that almost destroyed their marriage\".<ref name=icky/> Mamie and Dwight blamed themselves for Ikky's death; had they checked the girl's background, they would have found out that she had scarlet fever. In his biography of Eisenhower, [[Stephen E. Ambrose]] wrote:\n<blockquote>These feelings had to be suppressed if the marriage was to survive the disaster, but suppression did not eliminate the unwanted thoughts, only made them harder to live with. Both the inner-directed guilt and the projected feelings of blame placed a strain on their marriage. So did the equally inevitable sense of loss, the grief that could not be comforted, the feeling that all the joy had gone out of life. \"For a long time, it was as if a shining light had gone out in Ike's life,\" Mamie said later. \"Throughout all the years that followed, the memory of those bleak days was a deep inner pain that never seemed to diminish much.\"<ref name=icky/></blockquote>\n\nOn January 7, 1921, less than a week after his death, Ikky was buried in Fairmont Cemetery in [[Denver, Colorado]].<ref name=icky/> Eisenhower was mostly reticent to discuss his death.<ref name=\"beckett\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.whha.org/whha_publications/publications_documents/whitehousehistory_21.pdf | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605042420/http://www.whha.org/whha_publications/publications_documents/whitehousehistory_21.pdf | url-status=dead | archive-date=June 5, 2012 | title=President Eisenhower: Painter | author=Beckett, Wendy | journal=White House History | issue=21 | pages=30\u201340 | ref=harv }}</ref> In 1966, he was re-interred at the [[Eisenhower Presidential Center]]. His parents were buried next to him. In 1967, Eisenhower would look to Ikky's death as \"the greatest disappointment and disaster of my life, the one I have never been able to forget completely\".<ref name=icky/> For the rest of his life, he sent Mamie flowers on Ikky's birthday each year.<ref name=icky/>\n\n====John Eisenhower====\n{{main|John Eisenhower}}\nJohn Sheldon Doud Eisenhower (August 3, 1922 \u2013 December 21, 2013) was born in [[Denver, Colorado]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/john-sd-eisenhower-historian-and-presidents-son-dies-at-91/2013/12/21/2f344aae-6a9a-11e3-ae56-22de072140a2_story.html |title= John S.D. Eisenhower dies; historian and president's son was 91 |date=December 21, 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=August 16, 2017 |first1=Martin |last1=Weil |first2=Emily |last2=Langer }}</ref> John served in the [[United States Army]], his decorated military career spanned from before, during, and after his father's presidency, and he retired from active duty as a brigadier general in 1963 and then altogether in 1974. Coincidentally, John graduated from [[West Point]] on D-Day, June 6, 1944. After his military service, he became an author and military historian, and served as [[Diplomatic missions of Belgium|U.S. Ambassador to Belgium]] from 1969 to 1971, during the administration of President Richard Nixon, previously his father's vice president.\n\nJohn Eisenhower married Barbara Jean Thompson on June 10, 1947, only a few days before her twenty-first birthday. Barbara was born on June 15, 1926, in [[Fort Knox, Kentucky]], into an Army family. She was the daughter of [[Colonel|Col.]] Percy Walter Thompson (November 8, 1898&nbsp;\u2013 June 19, 1974) by his wife Beatrice (n\u00e9e Birchfield). Col. Thompson was commander of the Allied Expeditionary Forces. John and Barbara had four children: [[David Eisenhower|David]], Barbara Ann, [[Susan Eisenhower|Susan Elaine]], and [[Mary Jean Eisenhower|Mary Jean]]. David, after whom [[Camp David]] is named,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov/research/online_documents/camp_david.html |title=Camp David |publisher=Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum, and Boyhood Home |quote=Ike re-named it 'Camp David' in honor of his grandson David Eisenhower |access-date=August 16, 2017 |website=eisenhower.archives.gov }}</ref> married [[Richard Nixon]]'s daughter [[Julie Nixon Eisenhower|Julie]] in 1968.\n\nJohn and Barbara divorced in 1986 after thirty-nine years of marriage. In 1988, Barbara married widower Edwin J. Foltz, a former vice president at the [[Campbell Soup Company]]. She died on September 19, 2014, in [[Gladwyne]], [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]], [[Pennsylvania]].\n\nIn 1988, John married Joanne Thompson. He lived in [[Trappe, Maryland]], after moving there from [[Kimberton, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accuracyproject.org/cbe-Eisenhower,JohnSheldonDoud.html|title=John Sheldon Doud Eisenhower|publisher=Internet Accuracy Project|accessdate=November 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Extended family==\n===Grandchildren===\n[[File:Eisenhower julie david.jpg|thumb|Julie and David Eisenhower (age 23) in 1971.]]\n\n====David Eisenhower (1948\u2013present)====\n{{main|David Eisenhower}}\nDwight David Eisenhower II (born March 31, 1948), better known as [[David Eisenhower]] is an American author, public policy fellow, professor at the University of Pennsylvania, and eponym of the U.S. Presidential retreat, Camp David. He is the only grandson of Dwight D. Eisenhower, and the son-in-law of [[Richard Nixon]] by marriage to Nixon's daughter, [[Julie Nixon]]. The couple had three children: [[Jennie Elizabeth Eisenhower|Jennie Elizabeth]] (born August 15, 1978), an actress,<ref>{{IMDb name|id=1260502}}</ref> Alexander Richard (b. 1980) and Melanie Catherine Eisenhower (b. 1984).\n\n====Anne Eisenhower (1949\u2013present)====\n{{main|Anne Eisenhower}}\nBarbara Anne Eisenhower (born May 30, 1949), better known as [[Anne Eisenhower]], is a prominent interior designer based in [[New York City]], New York.<ref>{{Citation| last=Barbanel| first=Josh|title= Eisenhower Kin Sells Old Mansion In Southampton | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal| publication-place=New York City| date=11 December 2010| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704457604576011911688990794}}</ref>\n\nAnne 's first husband was Fernando Echavarr\u00eda-Uribe, an insurance executive from [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]], whom she met while vacationing in South America in 1966.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite magazine|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,841465,00.html|title=Milestones: Nov. 22, 1968|date=November 22, 1968|magazine=Time|via=content.time.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Intended\">\"Barbara's Intended\", ''The Burlington Free Press'' (October 28, 1968), p. 2.</ref> They married in November 1968,<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"Intended\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Women Are Headline Makers In Various Ways During 1968|publisher=The Shreveport Times|first=Patricia|last=McCormack|date=December 31, 1968|page=8}}</ref> and six months later had a daughter, Adriana Echavarr\u00eda (born May 29, 1969). Adriana became a photographer,<ref name=Evening>{{Citation| last=Yarrow| first=Andrew|title=The Evening Hours| newspaper=The New York Times| publication-place=New York City| date=2 January 1987| page=| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/02/style/the-evening-hours.html}}</ref> and was married for a time to Eduardo Mendoza de la Torre, the ex vice minister of justice in Colombia and later a vice president of Avianca Airlines, who was the only man to have ever testified against the notorious drug lord [[Pablo Escobar]].<ref name=Altar>{{Citation| last=| first=|title=Al altar| newspaper=Semana| publication-place=Bogot\u00e1, Colombia| date=13 December 1993| page=| url=http://www.semana.com/gente/articulo/al-altar/21326-3}}</ref> Through Adriana, Anna has two grandchildren, Camila and Nicol\u00e1s Mendoza-Eisenhower.\n\nIn the 1980s, Anne married [[Wolfgang Fl\u00f6ttl]], a billionaire hedge-fund manager who once owned an art collection with pieces by Van Gogh, Picasso, and C\u00e9zanne.<ref name=Hedge>{{Citation| last1=Crawford| first1=David| last2=Mollenkamp| first2=Carrick|title = How a Hedge-Fund Mogul Disrupted an Austrian Bank | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal| publication-place=New York City| date=25 January 2007| page=| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB116186493590604582}}</ref> Anne filed for divorce from Fl\u00f6ttl in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/02/02/eisenhowers-granddaughter-splits-from-hedge-fund-hubby/|title=Eisenhower's granddaughter splits from hedge-fund hubby|first=Emily|last=Saul|date=February 2, 2018|publisher=[[New York Post]]}}</ref>\n\n====Susan Eisenhower (1951\u2013present)====\n{{main|Susan Eisenhower}}\nSusan Elaine Eisenhower (born December 31, 1951) is an American consultant, author, and expert on [[international security]], [[space policy]], [[energy industry|energy]], and [[Russia\u2013United States relations|relations between the Russian Federation and the United States of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saveamericastreasures.org/eisenhower.htm|title=Plan your next trip with the National Trust \u2013 National Trust for Historic Preservation|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/programs/npc/2002/020211.seisenhower.html|title=NPR : Susan Eisenhower, National Press Club|first=Gretchen Cook, Thea|last=Joselow|website=www.npr.org|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"mdeath\">{{cite news |last1=Krebs |first1=Alvin |title=Mamie Eisenhower Dies in Sleep  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/11/02/archives/mamie-eisenhower-dies-in-sleep-at-82-in-hospital-in-washington.html |accessdate=23 March 2019 |work=New York Times |date=1979-11-02}}</ref>\n\nSusan has been married three times, first to Alexander H. Bradshaw, a London barrister,  with whom she has two children,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-01-05/news/mn-418_1_susan-eisenhower|title=Ike's Granddaughter to Wed Soviet Space Scientist :  Nuptials: Susan Eisenhower and Roald Sagdeev plan to maintain homes in Moscow and Washington.|first=From Times Wire|last=Services|date=5 January 1990|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2018|via=LA Times}}</ref> secondly to John Mahon, an American lawyer, with whom she had a daughter, Amelia Eisenhower Mahon,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20116771,00.html|title=After Glasnost, Romance: a Russian Scientist Marries Ike's Granddaughter Susan|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref> and finally to Russian space scientist [[Roald Sagdeev]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samford.edu/schools/artsci/comarts/davislecture/Eisenhower2002.htm|title=\"Leadership in Conflict\".|publisher=Samford University|accessdate=26 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012004231/http://www.samford.edu/schools/artsci/comarts/davislecture/Eisenhower2002.htm|archive-date=12 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> formerly the director of the [[Russian Space Research Institute]], [[Hero of Socialist Labour|Hero of Socialist Labor]], and pro-democracy advocate.<ref>Sagdeev, Roald (1994). The Making of a Soviet Scientist: My Adventures in Nuclear Fusion and Space From Stalin to Star Wars. Wiley. {{ISBN|0471020311}}.</ref>\n\n====Mary Jean Eisenhower (1955\u2013present)====\n{{main|Mary Jean Eisenhower}}\nMary Jean Eisenhower (born December 21, 1955) is an American humanitarian. She is the president and chief executive officer (and former [[President (corporate title)|president]] and [[Chairperson|chairman]] [[emeritus]]) of [[People to People International]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Larsen|first=Douglas|title=Mary Jane Eisenhower Enters Life Facing Two Demanding Traditions|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MwEsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gsYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5377,3254044&dq=mary-jean-eisenhower&hl=en|accessdate=June 3, 2017|newspaper=Florence Times|date=December 28, 1955|page=Section 2 Page 3}}</ref>\n\nShe married Army 2nd Lt. James Brewton Millard in May 1976, at a private military ceremony in Valley Forge, Pennsylvania, attended by her grandmother, former First Lady Mamie Eisenhower.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1665&dat=19760531&id=tZJPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YiUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2221,3642442&hl=en |title=Mary Eisenhower Wed |newspaper=The Times-News |location=[[Hendersonville, North Carolina]] |date=May 31, 1976 |access-date=June 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Books==\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Ambrose\n  | first = Stephen Edward\n  | authorlink = Stephen E. Ambrose\n  | title = Eisenhower: Soldier and President\n  | publisher = Simon & Schuster\n  | year = 1990\n  | location = [[New York City|New York]]\n  | pages = \n  | url = https://archive.org/details/eisenhower00ambr_0\n  | isbn = 0-671-70107-X\n  | url-access = registration\n  }}\n\n{{Dwight D. Eisenhower}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eisenhower, Dwight David, Family of}}\n[[Category:Eisenhower family|*]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss-German descent]]\n[[Category:Dwight D. Eisenhower]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|List of members of the family of Dwight D. Eisenhower}}\n{{Infobox family\n| name          = The Eisenhower family\n| image         = Birthday Party for Anne Eisenhower-cropped.jpg\n| image_size    = 250\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Birthday Party for granddaughter Anne Eisenhower (not shown). From left to right around the table: [[John Eisenhower]], [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], [[Mamie Eisenhower]], [[Barbara Eisenhower]], and [[David Eisenhower]] with his back to the camera.\n| region        = United States ([[Texas]], [[Kansas]], [[Washington, D.C.]])\n| early_forms   =\n| members       = [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], [[Mamie Eisenhower]], [[David Eisenhower]], [[Anne Eisenhower]], [[Susan Eisenhower]], [[Mary Jean Eisenhower]]\n| otherfamilies = \n| distinctions  =\n| traditions    = \n| heirlooms     =\n| estate        =\n| meaning       =\n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\nThe family of [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]<!-- No bolding! See MOS:BOLDTITLE -->, the 34th [[President of the United States]], and his wife. [[Mamie Eisenhower|Mamie]], is made up of people of [[German people|German]] and [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] descent. They are related by marriage to the family of [[Richard Nixon]], who was Eisenhower's vice-president, and was later the 37th president of the United States.\n\n==Family tree==\n{{Eisenhower family tree|1=extended}}\n\n== Family background ==\n[[File:Eisenhower House.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|The Eisenhower family home, [[Abilene, Kansas]]]]\nThe Eisenhauer (German for \"iron hewer/miner\") family migrated from [[Karlsbrunn]] in [[Nassau-Saarbr\u00fccken]], to America, first settling in [[York, Pennsylvania]], in 1741, and in the 1880s moving to Kansas.<ref name=\"barnett19421109\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JUAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA112| title=General \"Ike\" Eisenhower | work=Life | date=November 9, 1942 | accessdate=May 31, 2011 | author=Barnett, Lincoln | page=112}}</ref> Accounts vary as to how and when the German name Eisenhauer was [[anglicized]] to Eisenhower.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YVD0jK03EPEC | title=Ike: An American Hero | author=Korda, Michael | year=2007 | accessdate=July 22, 2012 | page=63}}</ref> Eisenhower's [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] ancestors, who were primarily farmers, included Hans Nikolaus Eisenhauer of Karlsbrunn, who migrated to [[Lancaster, Pennsylvania]], in 1741.<ref name=\"Ambrose 1983, p. 14\">{{harvnb|Ambrose|1983|p=14}}</ref>\n\n==Parents and siblings==\n{{main|Ida Stover Eisenhower}}\nThe great grandson of Hans Nikolaus Eisenhauer was Jacob Eisenhower, a Kansas farmer. Jacob's son, David Jacob Eisenhower (1863\u20131942), was Dwight D. Eisenhower's father. David Jacob was a college-educated engineer, despite his own father Jacob's urging to stay on the family farm. David owned a general store in [[Hope, Kansas]], but the business failed due to economic conditions and the family became impoverished. The Eisenhowers then lived in Texas from 1889 until 1892, and later returned to Kansas, with $24 ({{Inflation|US|24|1892|fmt=eq}}) to their name at the time. David worked as a railroad mechanic and then at a creamery.<ref name=\"Ambrose 1983, pp. 16\u20138\" />\n\nEisenhower's mother, [[Ida Stover Eisenhower|Ida Elizabeth (Stover) Eisenhower]], born in Virginia, of German Protestant ancestry, moved to Kansas from Virginia. She married David on September 23, 1885, in [[Lecompton, Kansas]], on the campus of their alma mater, [[Lane University]].<ref name=\"Ambrose 1983, pp. 16\u20138\">{{harvnb|Ambrose|1983|pp=16\u20138}}</ref>\n\nBy 1898, the parents made a decent living and provided a suitable home for their large family.<ref>{{harvnb|Ambrose|1983|p=19}}</ref> They had seven children, all sons, of whom one died in infancy.\n\n*Arthur Eisenhower (1886\u2013January 27, 1958)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/01/27/archives/arthur-eisenhower-dies-in-kansas-city-a-b-eisenhower-dies-in.html|title=Arthur Eisenhower Dies in Kansas City; A. B. EISENHOWER DIES IN MISSOURI|first=the Associated|last=Press|date=27 January 1958|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n*[[Edgar Newton Eisenhower]] (January 19, 1889 \u2013 July 12, 1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/07/13/archives/edgar-e-isenhower-late-presidents-b-tother-dies-lawyer-21-months.html|title=Edgar Eisenhower, Late President's Brother, Dies|date=13 July 1971|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n*Dwight David Eisenhower (October 14, 1890 \u2013 March 28, 1969)\n*Roy Eisenhower (1892\u2013June 7, 1942)<ref>Carlo D'Este, ''Eisenhower: A Soldier's Life'' (2003), p. 298.</ref>\n*[[Earl Dewey Eisenhower]] (February 1, 1898 \u2013 December 18, 1968)\n*[[Milton Stover Eisenhower]] (September 15, 1899 \u2013 May 2, 1985)\n*Paul Dawson Eisenhower (May 12, 1894 \u2013 March 16, 1895)\n\nOf these, Milton was the most notable of the brothers other than Dwight. Milton became an American educational administrator, serving as president of three major American universities: [[Kansas State University]] (1943\u20131950), [[Pennsylvania State University]] (1950\u20131956), and [[Johns Hopkins University]] (1956\u20131957). On October 12, 1927, Eisenhower married Helen Elsie Eakin (1904\u20131954), with whom he had a son, Milton Stover Eisenhower, Jr., in 1930 and a daughter, Ruth Eakin Eisenhower, in 1938.\n\nEarl also achieved a measure of notability, having been elected to a term in the Illinois House of Representatives, from 1965 to 1967. Earl married Kathryn McIntyre Snyder in 1933, with whom he had two children.\n\nEdgar graduated from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1914,<ref>''Who's Who in America, Volume XXX 1958-1959'' (1958). Chicago: A.N. Marquis Co.</ref> and began practicing law in 1915 in [[Tacoma, Washington]]; he became was known as a \"shoot from the hip ultraconservative.\"<ref>Obituary from the Kansas City ''Times'', July 13, 1971</ref> Edgar was married three times, first to Louise Alexander Eisenhower (1893\u20131946) in 1911, then to Bernice Thompson Eisenhower (1902\u20131948) in 1930, and finally to Lucille Dawson Eisenhower (1921\u20132012) in 1951. Edgar had two children, both with his first wife, Merrill Jack Eisenhower (1916\u20131956), and Janis Louise Eisenhower Causin (1922\u20132000).\n\n==Immediate family==\n<!--Please don't remove [[Template:Anchor|anchor template]] (or edit the name within their doubled, curly brackets). Thanks!-->\n\n===Mamie Eisenhower===\n[[File:Mamie eisenhower.gif|thumb|upright=0.9|Mamie Eisenhower, painted in 1953 by Thomas E. Stephens]]\n{{main|Mamie Eisenhower}}\nWhile Eisenhower was stationed in Texas, he met [[Mamie Eisenhower|Mamie Doud]] of [[Boone, Iowa]].{{r|barnett19421109}}\n\nDoud was the second child born to John Sheldon Doud (1870\u20131951), a [[Meat packing industry|meatpacking]] executive, and his wife, Elivera Mathilda Carlson (1878\u20131960).<ref name=\"Susan Eisenhower 2002\">Susan Eisenhower, \"Mrs. Ike: Memories and Reflections on the Life of Mamie Eisenhower\" (Capitol Books, 2002)</ref><ref name=nrhp>{{cite web |url=http://www.coloradohistory-oahp.org/programareas/register/1503/cty/pdfs/5DV747.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form |author=Tatanka Historical Associates |access-date=February 4, 2009 |work=www.coloradohistory-oahp.org |publisher=Colorado Historical Society Office of Archeology & Historic Preservation |date=February 25, 2005 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060816015657/http://www.coloradohistory-oahp.org/programareas/register/1503/cty/pdfs/5DV747.pdf |archive-date=August 16, 2006 }}</ref> She grew up in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]], [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], [[Denver, Colorado]], and the Doud winter home in [[San Antonio, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstladies.org/biographies/firstladies.aspx?biography=35 |title=Mamie Eisenhower Biography |publisher=National First Ladies Library |access-date=December 27, 2013 }}</ref> Her father, who retired at age 36, ran a meatpacking company founded by his father, Doud & Montgomery (\"Buyers of Live Hogs\"), and had investments in Illinois and Iowa stockyards.<ref name=\"Susan Eisenhower 2002\"/> Her mother was a daughter of Swedish immigrants.<ref name=\"Susan Eisenhower 2002\"/> She had three sisters: Eleanor Carlson Doud, Eda Mae Doud, and Mabel Frances \"Mike\" Doud.<ref name=\"Susan Eisenhower 2002\"/><ref name=nrhp />\n\nDoud and Eisenhower were immediately taken with each other. He proposed to her on Valentine's Day in 1916.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/publications/publicroads/03mar/05.cfm | title =The Man Who Changed America, Part I | author =Richard F. Weingroff | publisher =fhwa.dot.gov | date =March\u2013April 2003}}</ref> A November wedding date in Denver was moved up to July 1 due to the pending U.S. entry into World War&nbsp;I. They moved many times during their first 35 years of marriage.<ref>{{harvnb|Ambrose|1983|pp=59\u201360}}</ref>\n\n===Children===\nThe Eisenhowers had two sons, Doud Dwight \"Icky\" Eisenhower, and John Eisenhower.\n\n====Doud Eisenhower====\n[[File:Doudeisenhower.jpg|thumb|Doud with his parents, [[Mamie Eisenhower|Mamie]] and [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Dwight]].]]\n\nDoud Dwight Eisenhower (September 24, 1917&nbsp;\u2013 January 2, 1921) was the first son of Dwight and Mamie Eisenhower. He was named \"Doud\" in honor of his mother (whose maiden name was Doud) and \"Dwight\" in honor of his father. He was commonly called \"Ikky\" (pronounced as \"icky\") by his parents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/12/upshot/ike-and-his-sons-the-grief-of-a-supreme-commander-and-a-father.html |title=D-Day Wasn't the First Time Eisenhower Felt as if He Had Lost a Son |newspaper=The New York Times |first=Michael |last=Beschloss |department=The Upshot |date=June 11, 2014 |access-date=June 16, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=Berger-Knorr, Lawrence|title=The Pennsylvania Relations of Dwight D. Eisenhower|page=8}}</ref>\n\nDoud was born in [[San Antonio, Texas]], then he and his mother moved to [[Denver]], [[Colorado]] while his father was stationed at [[Fort George G. Meade|Camp Meade]] in [[Maryland]].<ref name=icky>{{cite web |url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/infrastructure/ichy.cfm |title=Icky |publisher=Federal Highway Administration |work=www.fhwa.dot.gov |accessdate=November 24, 2011 }}</ref> Regarding Dwight's family contacts while on the U.S. Army's 1919 [[Transcontinental Motor Convoy]], biographers Lester and Irene David wrote:\n<blockquote>He called Mamie several times a week [while on the convoy], beginning each call with requests for news about Icky. How was he growing? What new mischief had he gotten into? Once Mamie interrupted with, \"Listen here...how about asking how your wife is?\" Chastened; Ike chatted for a moment about Mamie but soon turned the conversation to Icky again. Mamie gave up.<ref name=icky/></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Eisenhowerdoudd.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Grave of Doud Dwight Eisenhower in [[Eisenhower Presidential Center|Eisenhower Center]]]]\nAfter he and his family relocated to [[Fort George G. Meade|Fort Meade]] in [[Severn, Maryland|Severn]], [[Maryland]], his mother hired a 16-year-old local girl as a maid. She had been recovering from [[scarlet fever]].<ref name=icky/> In December 1920, shortly before [[Christmas]], Ikky caught scarlet fever from her.<ref name=icky/> Though his mother tried desperately to save him, even calling a specialist from [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]] in [[Baltimore]],<ref name=icky/> Ikky died on January 2, 1921. His [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|father]] referred to this incident as \"the most shattering moment of their lives, one that almost destroyed their marriage\".<ref name=icky/> Mamie and Dwight blamed themselves for Ikky's death; had they checked the girl's background, they would have found out that she had scarlet fever. In his biography of Eisenhower, [[Stephen E. Ambrose]] wrote:\n<blockquote>These feelings had to be suppressed if the marriage was to survive the disaster, but suppression did not eliminate the unwanted thoughts, only made them harder to live with. Both the inner-directed guilt and the projected feelings of blame placed a strain on their marriage. So did the equally inevitable sense of loss, the grief that could not be comforted, the feeling that all the joy had gone out of life. \"For a long time, it was as if a shining light had gone out in Ike's life,\" Mamie said later. \"Throughout all the years that followed, the memory of those bleak days was a deep inner pain that never seemed to diminish much.\"<ref name=icky/></blockquote>\n\nOn January 7, 1921, less than a week after his death, Ikky was buried in Fairmont Cemetery in [[Denver, Colorado]].<ref name=icky/> Eisenhower was mostly reticent to discuss his death.<ref name=\"beckett\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.whha.org/whha_publications/publications_documents/whitehousehistory_21.pdf | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605042420/http://www.whha.org/whha_publications/publications_documents/whitehousehistory_21.pdf | url-status=dead | archive-date=June 5, 2012 | title=President Eisenhower: Painter | author=Beckett, Wendy | journal=White House History | issue=21 | pages=30\u201340 | ref=harv }}</ref> In 1966, he was re-interred at the [[Eisenhower Presidential Center]]. His parents were buried next to him. In 1967, Eisenhower would look to Ikky's death as \"the greatest disappointment and disaster of my life, the one I have never been able to forget completely\".<ref name=icky/> For the rest of his life, he sent Mamie flowers on Ikky's birthday each year.<ref name=icky/>\n\n====John Eisenhower====\n{{main|John Eisenhower}}\nJohn Sheldon Doud Eisenhower (August 3, 1922 \u2013 December 21, 2013) was born in [[Denver, Colorado]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/john-sd-eisenhower-historian-and-presidents-son-dies-at-91/2013/12/21/2f344aae-6a9a-11e3-ae56-22de072140a2_story.html |title= John S.D. Eisenhower dies; historian and president's son was 91 |date=December 21, 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=August 16, 2017 |first1=Martin |last1=Weil |first2=Emily |last2=Langer }}</ref> John served in the [[United States Army]], his decorated military career spanned from before, during, and after his father's presidency, and he retired from active duty as a brigadier general in 1963 and then altogether in 1974. Coincidentally, John graduated from [[West Point]] on D-Day, June 6, 1944. After his military service, he became an author and military historian, and served as [[Diplomatic missions of Belgium|U.S. Ambassador to Belgium]] from 1969 to 1971, during the administration of President Richard Nixon, previously his father's vice president.\n\nJohn Eisenhower married Barbara Jean Thompson on June 10, 1947, only a few days before her twenty-first birthday. Barbara was born on June 15, 1926, in [[Fort Knox, Kentucky]], into an Army family. She was the daughter of [[Colonel|Col.]] Percy Walter Thompson (November 8, 1898&nbsp;\u2013 June 19, 1974) by his wife Beatrice (n\u00e9e Birchfield). Col. Thompson was commander of the Allied Expeditionary Forces. John and Barbara had four children: [[David Eisenhower|David]], Barbara Ann, [[Susan Eisenhower|Susan Elaine]], and [[Mary Jean Eisenhower|Mary Jean]]. David, after whom [[Camp David]] is named,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov/research/online_documents/camp_david.html |title=Camp David |publisher=Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum, and Boyhood Home |quote=Ike re-named it 'Camp David' in honor of his grandson David Eisenhower |access-date=August 16, 2017 |website=eisenhower.archives.gov }}</ref> married [[Richard Nixon]]'s daughter [[Julie Nixon Eisenhower|Julie]] in 1968.\n\nJohn and Barbara divorced in 1986 after thirty-nine years of marriage. In 1988, Barbara married widower Edwin J. Foltz, a former vice president at the [[Campbell Soup Company]]. She died on September 19, 2014, in [[Gladwyne]], [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]], [[Pennsylvania]].\n\nIn 1988, John married Joanne Thompson. He lived in [[Trappe, Maryland]], after moving there from [[Kimberton, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accuracyproject.org/cbe-Eisenhower,JohnSheldonDoud.html|title=John Sheldon Doud Eisenhower|publisher=Internet Accuracy Project|accessdate=November 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Extended family==\n===Grandchildren===\n[[File:Eisenhower julie david.jpg|thumb|Julie and David Eisenhower (age 23) in 1971.]]\n\n====David Eisenhower (1948\u2013present)====\n{{main|David Eisenhower}}\nDwight David Eisenhower II (born March 31, 1948), better known as [[David Eisenhower]] is an American author, public policy fellow, professor at the University of Pennsylvania, and eponym of the U.S. Presidential retreat, Camp David. He is the only grandson of Dwight D. Eisenhower, and the son-in-law of [[Richard Nixon]] by marriage to Nixon's daughter, [[Julie Nixon]]. The couple had three children: [[Jennie Elizabeth Eisenhower|Jennie Elizabeth]] (born August 15, 1978), an actress,<ref>{{IMDb name|id=1260502}}</ref> Alexander Richard (b. 1980) and Melanie Catherine Eisenhower (b. 1984).\n\n====Anne Eisenhower (1949\u2013present)====\n{{main|Anne Eisenhower}}\nBarbara Anne Eisenhower (born May 30, 1949), better known as [[Anne Eisenhower]], is a prominent interior designer based in [[New York City]], New York.<ref>{{Citation| last=Barbanel| first=Josh|title= Eisenhower Kin Sells Old Mansion In Southampton | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal| publication-place=New York City| date=11 December 2010| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704457604576011911688990794}}</ref>\n\nAnne 's first husband was Fernando Echavarr\u00eda-Uribe, an insurance executive from [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]], whom she met while vacationing in South America in 1966.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite magazine|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,841465,00.html|title=Milestones: Nov. 22, 1968|date=November 22, 1968|magazine=Time|via=content.time.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Intended\">\"Barbara's Intended\", ''The Burlington Free Press'' (October 28, 1968), p. 2.</ref> They married in November 1968,<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"Intended\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Women Are Headline Makers In Various Ways During 1968|publisher=The Shreveport Times|first=Patricia|last=McCormack|date=December 31, 1968|page=8}}</ref> and six months later had a daughter, Adriana Echavarr\u00eda (born May 29, 1969). Adriana became a photographer,<ref name=Evening>{{Citation| last=Yarrow| first=Andrew|title=The Evening Hours| newspaper=The New York Times| publication-place=New York City| date=2 January 1987| page=| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/02/style/the-evening-hours.html}}</ref> and was married for a time to Eduardo Mendoza de la Torre, the ex vice minister of justice in Colombia and later a vice president of Avianca Airlines, who was the only man to have ever testified against the notorious drug lord [[Pablo Escobar]].<ref name=Altar>{{Citation| last=| first=|title=Al altar| newspaper=Semana| publication-place=Bogot\u00e1, Colombia| date=13 December 1993| page=| url=http://www.semana.com/gente/articulo/al-altar/21326-3}}</ref> Through Adriana, Anna has two grandchildren, Camila and Nicol\u00e1s Mendoza-Eisenhower.\n\nIn the 1980s, Anne married [[Wolfgang Fl\u00f6ttl]], a billionaire hedge-fund manager who once owned an art collection with pieces by Van Gogh, Picasso, and C\u00e9zanne.<ref name=Hedge>{{Citation| last1=Crawford| first1=David| last2=Mollenkamp| first2=Carrick|title = How a Hedge-Fund Mogul Disrupted an Austrian Bank | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal| publication-place=New York City| date=25 January 2007| page=| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB116186493590604582}}</ref> Anne filed for divorce from Fl\u00f6ttl in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/02/02/eisenhowers-granddaughter-splits-from-hedge-fund-hubby/|title=Eisenhower's granddaughter splits from hedge-fund hubby|first=Emily|last=Saul|date=February 2, 2018|publisher=[[New York Post]]}}</ref>\n\n====Susan Eisenhower (1951\u2013present)====\n{{main|Susan Eisenhower}}\nSusan Elaine Eisenhower (born December 31, 1951) is an American consultant, author, and expert on [[international security]], [[space policy]], [[energy industry|energy]], and [[Russia\u2013United States relations|relations between the Russian Federation and the United States of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saveamericastreasures.org/eisenhower.htm|title=Plan your next trip with the National Trust \u2013 National Trust for Historic Preservation|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/programs/npc/2002/020211.seisenhower.html|title=NPR : Susan Eisenhower, National Press Club|first=Gretchen Cook, Thea|last=Joselow|website=www.npr.org|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"mdeath\">{{cite news |last1=Krebs |first1=Alvin |title=Mamie Eisenhower Dies in Sleep  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/11/02/archives/mamie-eisenhower-dies-in-sleep-at-82-in-hospital-in-washington.html |accessdate=23 March 2019 |work=New York Times |date=1979-11-02}}</ref>\n\nSusan has been married three times, first to Alexander H. Bradshaw, a London barrister,  with whom she has two children,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-01-05/news/mn-418_1_susan-eisenhower|title=Ike's Granddaughter to Wed Soviet Space Scientist :  Nuptials: Susan Eisenhower and Roald Sagdeev plan to maintain homes in Moscow and Washington.|first=From Times Wire|last=Services|date=5 January 1990|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2018|via=LA Times}}</ref> secondly to John Mahon, an American lawyer, with whom she had a daughter, Amelia Eisenhower Mahon,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20116771,00.html|title=After Glasnost, Romance: a Russian Scientist Marries Ike's Granddaughter Susan|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref> and finally to Russian space scientist [[Roald Sagdeev]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samford.edu/schools/artsci/comarts/davislecture/Eisenhower2002.htm|title=\"Leadership in Conflict\".|publisher=Samford University|accessdate=26 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012004231/http://www.samford.edu/schools/artsci/comarts/davislecture/Eisenhower2002.htm|archive-date=12 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> formerly the director of the [[Russian Space Research Institute]], [[Hero of Socialist Labour|Hero of Socialist Labor]], and pro-democracy advocate.<ref>Sagdeev, Roald (1994). The Making of a Soviet Scientist: My Adventures in Nuclear Fusion and Space From Stalin to Star Wars. Wiley. {{ISBN|0471020311}}.</ref>\n\n====Mary Jean Eisenhower (1955\u2013present)====\n{{main|Mary Jean Eisenhower}}\nMary Jean Eisenhower (born December 21, 1955) is an American humanitarian. She is the president and chief executive officer (and former [[President (corporate title)|president]] and [[Chairperson|chairman]] [[emeritus]]) of [[People to People International]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Larsen|first=Douglas|title=Mary Jane Eisenhower Enters Life Facing Two Demanding Traditions|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MwEsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gsYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5377,3254044&dq=mary-jean-eisenhower&hl=en|accessdate=June 3, 2017|newspaper=Florence Times|date=December 28, 1955|page=Section 2 Page 3}}</ref>\n\nShe married Army 2nd Lt. James Brewton Millard in May 1976, at a private military ceremony in Valley Forge, Pennsylvania, attended by her grandmother, former First Lady Mamie Eisenhower.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1665&dat=19760531&id=tZJPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YiUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2221,3642442&hl=en |title=Mary Eisenhower Wed |newspaper=The Times-News |location=[[Hendersonville, North Carolina]] |date=May 31, 1976 |access-date=June 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Books==\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Ambrose\n  | first = Stephen Edward\n  | authorlink = Stephen E. Ambrose\n  | title = Eisenhower: Soldier and President\n  | publisher = Simon & Schuster\n  | year = 1990\n  | location = [[New York City|New York]]\n  | pages = \n  | url = https://archive.org/details/eisenhower00ambr_0\n  | isbn = 0-671-70107-X\n  | url-access = registration\n  }}\n\n{{Dwight D. Eisenhower}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eisenhower, Dwight David, Family of}}\n[[Category:Eisenhower family|*]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss-German descent]]\n[[Category:Dwight D. Eisenhower]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:5b40:36c0:bcd2:21b:780f:a14e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(fake trashness)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Family_of_Dwight_D._Eisenhower"}
{"title_page": "Philip Odeen", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2012}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2012}}\n\n}}\n\n'''Phil A. Odeen''' is a member of the board of directors at [[Northrop Grumman]]. He holds many other corporate and government positions.\n\n==History==\nOdeen graduated [[Phi Beta Kappa]] from the [[University of South Dakota]] in 1957. He was a [[Fulbright Scholar]] to the [[United Kingdom]], and earned a [[Master's degree]] in 1959 from the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]. He soon became involved in government  He served in senior positions under the [[Nixon administration]] on the staff for the [[Secretary of Defense]] and the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]]. He was Principal Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense, and worked directly under [[Henry Kissinger]] with responsibility for Defense and arms Control issues  \n\nFrom 1972 to 1978 Odeen was Vice President of [[Wilson Sporting Goods]]. Odeen was a managing partner of [[Coopers & Lybrand]] from 1978 to 1991, and then became vice chair of their management consulting services until 1992. He then became president and CEO of BDM International, where he tripled the value of the company in five years.\n\nIn 1997, [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] [[William Cohen]] selected Odeen to chair the [[National Defense Panel]]. Also in 1997 the [[TRW Inc.|TRW]] corporation acquired BDM, and Odeen became executive vice president and general manager of [[Information Technology]] at TRW. He was senior representative in [[Washington D.C.]], responsible for government relations, business development and selected international activities of the Aerospace and Information Systems sector. This correlated well with his position in government. He retired as chairman of TRW in 2002, when [[Northrop Grumman]] took over the company in a $7.8 billion merger.\n\n==Current activities==\nIn 2003, Odeen became a member of Northrop Grumman's board of directors, a position he still holds. He also serves on the boards [[Avaya]], [[Convergys]], [[Reynolds and Reynolds]], and [[Washington Gas Light Company]]. Odeen was named as Avaya's nonexecutive Chairman of the Board of Directors on October 1, 2006. Odeen is a member of the U.S. government's [[Defense Science Board]], and is a former Vice President of that board. He is a member of the Chief of Naval Operations Executive Panel, and is active in various other government advisory groups.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odeen, Philip}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American financial businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Directors of Northrop Grumman]]\n[[Category:University of South Dakota alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2012}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2012}}\n\n}}\n\n'''Phil A. Odeen''' is a member of the board of directors at [[Northrop Grumman]]. He holds many other corporate and government positions.\n\n==History==\nOdeen graduated [[Phi Beta Kappa]] from the [[University of South Dakota]] in 1957. He was a [[Fulbright Scholar]] to the [[United Kingdom]], and earned a [[Master's degree]] in 1959 from the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]. He soon became involved in politics. He served in senior positions under the [[Nixon administration]] as staff for the [[Secretary of Defense]] and the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]]. He was Principal Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense, and worked directly under [[Henry Kissinger]]. \n\nFrom 1972 to 1978 Odeen was Vice President of [[Wilson Sporting Goods]]. Odeen was a managing partner of [[Coopers & Lybrand]] from 1978 to 1991, and then became vice chair of their management consulting services until 1992. He then became president and CEO of BDM International, where he tripled the value of the company in five years.\n\nIn 1997, [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] [[William Cohen]] selected Odeen to chair the [[National Defense Panel]]. Also in 1997 the [[TRW Inc.|TRW]] corporation acquired BDM, and Odeen became executive vice president and general manager of [[Information Technology]] at TRW. He was senior representative in [[Washington D.C.]], responsible for government relations, business development and selected international activities of the Aerospace and Information Systems sector. This correlated well with his position in government. He retired as chairman of TRW in 2002, when [[Northrop Grumman]] took over the company in a $7.8 billion merger.\n\n==Current activities==\nIn 2003, Odeen became a member of Northrop Grumman's board of directors, a position he still holds. He also serves on the boards [[Avaya]], [[Convergys]], [[Reynolds and Reynolds]], and [[Washington Gas Light Company]]. Odeen was named as Avaya's nonexecutive Chairman of the Board of Directors on October 1, 2006. Odeen is a member of the U.S. government's [[Defense Science Board]], and is a former Vice President of that board. He is a member of the Chief of Naval Operations Executive Panel, and is active in various other government advisory groups.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odeen, Philip}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American financial businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Directors of Northrop Grumman]]\n[[Category:University of South Dakota alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n", "name_user": "Podeen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected some items and added material", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_Odeen"}
{"title_page": "Augusto Binelli", "text_new": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Gus Binelli\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| position = \n| height_ft = 7\n| height_in = 0.75\n| weight_lbs = 260\n| height_order= flip\n| weight_order= flip\n| league = \n| team = \n| number = \n| nationality = Italian\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1964|9|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Carrara]], Italy\n| high_school =  [[Long Island Lutheran Middle and High School|Long Island Lutheran]]<br>([[Brookville, New York]])\n| college = \n| draft_year   = 1986\n| draft_round  = 2\n| draft_pick   = 40\n| draft_team   = [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n| career_start = 1983\n| career_end = 2010\n| career_number = \n| career_position = [[Center (basketball)|Center]]\n| coach_start = 2011\n| coach_end = 2013\n| years1 = 1983\u20132000\t\n| team1 = [[Virtus Bologna]]\n| years2 = 2000\u20132001\t\n| team2 = Progresso Castelmaggiore\n| years3 = 2001\u20132002\t\n| team3 = [[Sutor Basket Montegranaro|Sutor Montegranaro]]\n| years4 = 2002\u20132004\t\n| team4 = [[Club Sportivo Pallacanestro Trapani|Trapani]]\n| years5 = 2004\u20132007\t\n| team5 = Benedetto XIV Cento\n| years6 = 2007\u20132009\t\n| team6 = Anzola\n| years7 = 2009\u20132010\t\n| team7 = Salus Bologna\n| cyears1 = 2011\u20132013\t\n| cteam1 = Anzola\n| highlights = \n'''As player:'''\n*[[EuroLeague]] champion (1998)\n*[[FIBA European Selection]] (1995)\n*[[FIBA Saporta Cup]] champion (1990)\n*5\u00d7 [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian League]] champion (1984, 1993\u20131995, 1998)\n*5\u00d7 [[Italian Basketball Cup|Italian Cup]] winner (1984, 1989, 1990, 1997, 1999)\n*[[Italian Basketball Supercup|Italian Supercup]] winner (1995)\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry | {{bk|ITA}}}}\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[Basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[EuroBasket 1985|1985 West Germany]] | }}}}\n\n'''Augusto \"Gus\" Binelli''' (born 1964) is a retired Italian professional [[basketball]] player and [[basketball coach|coach]].  At a height of {{height|m=2.15|frac=4}} tall, and a weight of {{convert|118|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, he played at the [[center (basketball)|center]] position. Binelli was [[NBA Draft|drafted]] in the second round, of the [[1986 NBA draft]], by the [[Atlanta Hawks]], though he never played in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]].\n\n==Professional career==\nBinelli played with the senior men's team of [[Virtus Bologna]], from 1980 to 2000. With Virtus Bologna, he won 5 [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian League]] championships (1984, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1998), 5 [[Italian Basketball Cup|Italian Cups]] (1984, 1989, 1990, 1997, 1999), the [[EuroLeague]] championship (1998), and the [[FIBA Saporta Cup|FIBA European Cup Cup Winner's Cup]] (FIBA Saporta Cup) (1990).  He was also a 2-time [[McDonald's Open]] finalist ([[1993 McDonald's Championship|1993]], [[1995 McDonald's Championship|1995]]).\n\nHe was a member of the [[FIBA European Selection]] team, in 1995.\n\n==Italian national team==\nBinelli played with the senior [[Italian national basketball team]], at the [[EuroBasket 1985]], where he won a bronze medal. He also played at the [[1986 FIBA World Championship]], and at the [[EuroBasket 1989]].\n\n==Awards and Accomplishments==\n===Clubs===\n*5\u00d7 [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian League]] Champion: (1984, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1998)\n*5\u00d7 [[Italian Basketball Cup|Italian Cup]] Winner: (1984, 1989, 1990, 1997, 1999)\n*[[FIBA Saporta Cup|FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup]] (FIBA Saporta Cup) Champion: (1990)\n*[[Italian Basketball Supercup|Italian Supercup]] Winner: (1995)\n*[[FIBA European Selection]]: (1995)\n*[[EuroLeague]] [[EuroLeague champion|Champion]]: (1998)\n\n===Italian senior national team===\n*[[1985 EuroBasket]]: {{bronze medal}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/rpp//q/Augusto%20Binelli/pid//_//players.html FIBA Profile]\n*[http://www.fibaeurope.com/compID_GSf9wrCdHBkDZZk9UQoqE3.season_2000.roundID_2532.playerID_7675.teamID_1315.html FIBA Europe Profile]\n*[http://web.legabasket.it/player/?id=BIN-AUG-64 Italian League Profile] {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{1986 NBA draft}}\n{{Virtus Bologna 1997\u201398 Euroleague champions}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Binelli, Augusto}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Hawks draft picks]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Italian basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Italian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Pallacanestro Trapani players]]\n[[Category:Sutor Basket Montegranaro players]]\n[[Category:Virtus Pallacanestro Bologna players]]\n\n{{Italy-basketball-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Gus Binelli\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| position = \n| height_ft = 7\n| height_in = 0.75\n| weight_lbs = 260\n| height_order= flip\n| weight_order= flip\n| league = \n| team = \n| number = \n| nationality = Italian\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1964|9|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Carrara]], Italy\n| high_school =  [[Long Island Lutheran Middle and High School|Long Island Lutheran]]<br>([[Brookville, New York]])\n| college = \n| draft_year   = 1986\n| draft_round  = 2\n| draft_pick   = 40\n| draft_team   = [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n| career_start = 1983\n| career_end = 2010\n| career_number = \n| career_position = [[Center (basketball)|Center]]\n| coach_start = 2011\n| coach_end = 2013\n| years1 = 1983\u20132000\t\n| team1 = [[Virtus Bologna]]\n| years2 = 2000\u20132001\t\n| team2 = Progresso Castelmaggiore\n| years3 = 2001\u20132002\t\n| team3 = [[Sutor Basket Montegranaro|Sutor Montegranaro]]\n| years4 = 2002\u20132004\t\n| team4 = [[Club Sportivo Pallacanestro Trapani|Trapani]]\n| years5 = 2004\u20132007\t\n| team5 = Benedetto XIV Cento\n| years6 = 2007\u20132009\t\n| team6 = Anzola\n| years7 = 2009\u20132010\t\n| team7 = Salus Bologna\n| cyears1 = 2011\u20132013\t\n| cteam1 = Anzola\n| highlights = \n'''As player:'''\n*[[EuroLeague]] champion (1998)\n*[[FIBA European Selection]] (1995)\n*[[FIBA Saporta Cup]] champion (1990)\n*5\u00d7 [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian League]] champion (1984, 1993\u20131995, 1998)\n*5\u00d7 [[Italian Basketball Cup|Italian Cup]] winner (1984, 1989, 1990, 1997, 1999)\n*[[Italian Basketball Supercup|Italian Supercup]] winner (1995)\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry | {{bk|ITA}}}}\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[Basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[EuroBasket 1985|1985 West Germany]] | }}}}\n\n'''Augusto \"Gus\" Binelli''' (born 1964) is a retired Italian professional [[basketball]] player and [[basketball coach|coach]].  At a height of {{height|m=2.15}} tall, and a weight of {{convert|118|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, he played at the [[center (basketball)|center]] position. Binelli was [[NBA Draft|drafted]] in the second round, of the [[1986 NBA draft]], by the [[Atlanta Hawks]], though he never played in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]].\n\n==Professional career==\nBinelli played with the senior men's team of [[Virtus Bologna]], from 1980 to 2000. With Virtus Bologna, he won 5 [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian League]] championships (1984, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1998), 5 [[Italian Basketball Cup|Italian Cups]] (1984, 1989, 1990, 1997, 1999), the [[EuroLeague]] championship (1998), and the [[FIBA Saporta Cup|FIBA European Cup Cup Winner's Cup]] (FIBA Saporta Cup) (1990).  He was also a 2-time [[McDonald's Open]] finalist ([[1993 McDonald's Championship|1993]], [[1995 McDonald's Championship|1995]]).\n\nHe was a member of the [[FIBA European Selection]] team, in 1995.\n\n==Italian national team==\nBinelli played with the senior [[Italian national basketball team]], at the [[EuroBasket 1985]], where he won a bronze medal. He also played at the [[1986 FIBA World Championship]], and at the [[EuroBasket 1989]].\n\n==Awards and Accomplishments==\n===Clubs===\n*5\u00d7 [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian League]] Champion: (1984, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1998)\n*5\u00d7 [[Italian Basketball Cup|Italian Cup]] Winner: (1984, 1989, 1990, 1997, 1999)\n*[[FIBA Saporta Cup|FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup]] (FIBA Saporta Cup) Champion: (1990)\n*[[Italian Basketball Supercup|Italian Supercup]] Winner: (1995)\n*[[FIBA European Selection]]: (1995)\n*[[EuroLeague]] [[EuroLeague champion|Champion]]: (1998)\n\n===Italian senior national team===\n*[[1985 EuroBasket]]: {{bronze medal}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/rpp//q/Augusto%20Binelli/pid//_//players.html FIBA Profile]\n*[http://www.fibaeurope.com/compID_GSf9wrCdHBkDZZk9UQoqE3.season_2000.roundID_2532.playerID_7675.teamID_1315.html FIBA Europe Profile]\n*[http://web.legabasket.it/player/?id=BIN-AUG-64 Italian League Profile] {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{1986 NBA draft}}\n{{Virtus Bologna 1997\u201398 Euroleague champions}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Binelli, Augusto}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Hawks draft picks]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Italian basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Italian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Pallacanestro Trapani players]]\n[[Category:Sutor Basket Montegranaro players]]\n[[Category:Virtus Pallacanestro Bologna players]]\n\n{{Italy-basketball-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Carnby", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augusto_Binelli"}
